Wash and dry produce.

Halve, peel, and dice @yellow onion{1}(diced). Trim and thinly slice @scallions{2}, 
separating whites from greens. Cut @cauliflower florets{10%oz} into bite-size pieces.

Heat a drizzle of @cooking oil{2%tsp} in a #medium pot{} (use a #large pot{} for 4 
servings) over medium heat. Add onion and a pinch of @salt{} and @pepper{}. Cook, 
stirring occasionally, until browned and softened, ~{3-4%minutes}.

> Add a splash of water if onion begins to brown too quickly.

Add scallion whites and @garlic powder{1%tsp}; cook, stirring frequently, until 
fragrant, ~{1%minute}.

Add another drizzle of oil to pot. Stir in @curry powder{1%tbsp}, @cumin{1%tsp},
@tomato paste{1.5%oz}, and half the @garam masala{1%tsp}(divided) until combined. 
Cook, stirring constantly, until fragrant, ~{30-60%seconds}.

Thoroughly shake @coconut milk{1} in container before opening.

To pot with veggies, stir in coconut milk, cauliflower, @chickpeas{1} and their 
liquid, @veggie stock concentrate{2}, 1 cup water (2 cups for 4 servings), and 
a big pinch of salt (we used 1 tsp; 2 tsp for 4). Bring to a simmer, then cover 
and reduce heat to medium low. Cook until cauliflower is almost tender, 
~{6%minutes}.

Uncover and cook, stirring occasionally, until soup has thickened, 
~{5-7%minutes} more.

> If your soup isn't thick enough, simmer until it reaches desired consistency. 
> If your soup is too thick, add a few splashes of water.

Taste and season with salt and pepper.

Meanwhile, halve @ciabatta{1}. Drizzle cut sides with @olive oil{1%tsp} and sprinkle 
with salt and pepper. Toast in a #griddle pan{} or #stove{} until golden; halve 
on a diagonal.

Divide soup between #bowls{}; sprinkle with scallion greens. Serve with toast 
on the side.

> Turn up the heat and give your dish a fiery attitude by adding chili flakes 
> from your pantry.